{"title_page": "Morriston Hospital", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox hospital\n| Name        = Morriston Hospital\n| Org/Group   = [[Swansea Bay University Health Board]]\n| Image       = Ysbyty Treforys. Morriston Hospital. - geograph.org.uk - 404965.jpg\n| Caption     = Morriston Hospital\n| Logo        =\n| location    = Heol Maes Eglwys, [[Cwmrhydyceirw]], [[Swansea]], Wales, United Kingdom\n| HealthCare  = [[NHS Wales]]\n| Type        = Teaching\n| Speciality  = \n| Standards   =\n| Emergency   = Yes\n| Affiliation = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Swansea University]]\n* [[Cardiff University]]\n}}\n| Beds        = 750\n| Founded     = 1942\n| Closed      =\n| website     = {{Official URL}}\n| Wiki-Links  = \n| map_type    = Wales Swansea\n| map_caption = Shown in Swansea\n| coordinates={{coord|51|40|56.00|N|3|56|02.00|W|type:landmark|display=inline,title}}\n|}}\n\n'''Morriston Hospital''' ({{lang-cy|Ysbyty Treforys}}) is a 750-bed hospital located in [[Cwmrhydyceirw]] near [[Morriston]] in [[Swansea]], Wales. It is managed by [[Swansea Bay University Health Board]].  Alongside its role as a district general hospital, Morriston is a teaching hospital for medical students of [[Swansea University Medical School]].\n\n==History==\nThe site was originally occupied by Maes-y-Gwernen Hall, a 19th century farmhouse which was acquired by [[William Williams (Swansea MP)|William Williams]] MP in 1885.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wales.nhs.uk/sitesplus/992/news/46132|title=Take a look inside as Maes-y-Gwernen Hall opens its doors|publisher=Llwchwr Community Network|date=14 September 2017|accessdate=9 February 2019}}</ref> Williams's son, [[Jeremiah Williams (British politician)|Jeremiah Williams]], inherited the house in 1904 and invited [[David Lloyd George]] to stay there in 1918.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wales.nhs.uk/sitesplus/992/news/43612|title=Morriston celebrates centenary of David Lloyd George becoming PM|date=21 December 2016|publisher=Llwchwr Community Network|accessdate=9 February 2019}}</ref> An emergency medical hospital was built on the site in 1942.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://coflein.gov.uk/en/site/418613/details/morriston-hospital-swansea|title=Morriston Hospital|publisher=Coflein|accessdate=9 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nBy the late 1970s the hospital needed modernising. The design, which was undertaken by William Simpson using a nucleus layout which was capable of expansion,<ref>[http://www.nuffieldtrust.org.uk/ecomm/files/50_years_of_ideas.pdf 50 Years of Ideas in health care buildings] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110511203413/http://www.nuffieldtrust.org.uk/ecomm/files/50_years_of_ideas.pdf |date=May 11, 2011 }}</ref> was announced in December 1976 and planning permission granted in March 1978.<ref>[http://www2.swansea.gov.uk/Northgate/PlanningExplorer/Generic/StdDetails.aspx?PT=Constraints&TYPE=PL/PlanningPK.xml&PARAM0=468472&XSLT=/Northgate/PlanningExplorer/SiteFiles/Skins/Swansea_noborder/xslt/PL/PLDetails.xslt&FT=Planning%20Details&DAURI=PLANNING&XMLSIDE=/Northgate/PlanningExplorer/SiteFiles/Skins/swansea_noborder/Menus/PL.xml Online Standard Details] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120220015623/http://www2.swansea.gov.uk/Northgate/PlanningExplorer/Generic/StdDetails.aspx?PT=Constraints&TYPE=PL%2FPlanningPK.xml&PARAM0=468472&XSLT=%2FNorthgate%2FPlanningExplorer%2FSiteFiles%2FSkins%2FSwansea_noborder%2Fxslt%2FPL%2FPLDetails.xslt&FT=Planning%20Details&DAURI=PLANNING&XMLSIDE=%2FNorthgate%2FPlanningExplorer%2FSiteFiles%2FSkins%2Fswansea_noborder%2FMenus%2FPL.xml |date=2012-02-20 }}. .swansea.gov.uk (1978-03-30). Retrieved on 2013-08-12.</ref> Construction began in 1981 and the building opened in October 1985.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/written_answers/1985/dec/19/hospitals-1#column_285w |title=Hospitals |publisher=Hansard|date= 19 December 1985|accessdate=9 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe Welsh Centre for Burns and Plastic Surgery, which was designed to provide care for the whole population of 2.3 million across [[West Wales|West]], [[Mid Wales|Mid]] and [[South Wales]], moved to the site from [[St Lawrence Hospital, Chepstow]] in 1994.<ref name=burns>{{cite web|url=http://www.wales.nhs.uk/sitesplus/863/page/39301|title=The Welsh Centre for Burns and Plastic Surgery|publisher=Abertawe Bro Morgannwg University Health Board|accessdate=9 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015 the Health Board announced plans to expand the site with focus exclusively on the care of the sickest patients.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-38893085|title=\u00a3600m Arch bid to 'transform' west Wales NHS|publisher=BBC|accessdate=9 February 2019}}</ref> Further to those plans, a new [[cardiac]] unit, built at a cost of \u00a36.6 million, opened in August 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.walesonline.co.uk/news/health/new-66m-hospital-cardiac-unit-11725852|title=New \u00a36.6m hospital cardiac unit is unveiled in a bid to improve surgery waiting times|publisher=Wales online|date=9 August 2016|accessdate=9 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Services==\nThe hospital is the site of the major Emergency Department for Swansea and is considered by the Health Board to be the major trauma centre for [[South West Wales]]. In addition to general surgical and medical services, Morriston houses the Welsh Centre for Burns and Plastic Surgery.<ref name=burns/>\n\nThe hospital successfully trialled the use of robotic process automation to review rheumatology prescriptions in 2019. The Welsh government plans to set up an e-prescribing system.<ref>{{cite news |title=Automation pilot cuts prescription checking time by two-thirds |url=https://www.pharmaceutical-journal.com/20207500.article? |accessdate=24 February 2020 |publisher=Pharmaceutical Journal |date=20 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Public transport==\nThe hospital is served by a regular bus service between Morriston Hospital and [[Singleton Hospital]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bustimes.org/services/4-singleton-hospital-morriston-hospital|title=Singleton Hospital - Morriston Hospital|publisher=Bus times|accessdate=9 February 2019}}</ref>\n{{ftrmetro start}}\n{{rail line|previous=Heol Maes Egwlys|next=Terminus|route=Morriston Hospital|col=5B16F0 }}\n{{s-end}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{Official website}}\n* [https://111.wales.nhs.uk/LocalServices/ViewLocalService.aspx?id=3122&s=Hospital Morriston Hospital on the NHS Direct Wales website]\n* [https://hiw.org.uk/morriston-hospital Healthcare Inspectorate Wales inspection reports]\n\n{{Swansea Bay University Health Board}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Hospital buildings completed in 1941]]\n[[Category:Hospital buildings completed in 1985]]\n[[Category:NHS hospitals in Wales]]\n[[Category:1942 establishments in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Hospitals with year of establishment missing]]\n[[Category:Hospitals established in 1942]]\n[[Category:Teaching hospitals in Wales]]\n[[Category:Hospitals in Swansea]]\n[[Category:Swansea Bay University Health Board]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox hospital\n| Name        = Morriston Hospital <br> Ysbyty Treforys\n| Org/Group   = [[Swansea Bay University Health Board]]\n| Image       = Ysbyty Treforys. Morriston Hospital. - geograph.org.uk - 404965.jpg\n| Caption     = Morriston Hospital\n| Logo        =\n| location    = Heol Maes Eglwys, [[Cwmrhydyceirw]], [[Swansea]], Wales, United Kingdom\n| HealthCare  = [[NHS Wales]]\n| Type        = Teaching\n| Speciality  = \n| Standards   =\n| Emergency   = Yes\n| Affiliation = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Swansea University]]\n* [[Cardiff University]]\n}}\n| Beds        = 750\n| Founded     = 1942\n| Closed      =\n| website     = {{Official URL}}\n| Wiki-Links  = \n| map_type    = Wales Swansea\n| map_caption = Shown in Swansea\n| coordinates={{coord|51|40|56.00|N|3|56|02.00|W|type:landmark|display=inline,title}}\n|}}\n\n'''Morriston Hospital''' ({{lang-cy|Ysbyty Treforys}}) is a 750-bed hospital located in [[Cwmrhydyceirw]] near [[Morriston]] in [[Swansea]], Wales. It is managed by [[Swansea Bay University Health Board]].  Alongside its role as a district general hospital, Morriston is a teaching hospital for medical students of [[Swansea University Medical School]].\n\n==History==\nThe site was originally occupied by Maes-y-Gwernen Hall, a 19th century farmhouse which was acquired by [[William Williams (Swansea MP)|William Williams]] MP in 1885.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wales.nhs.uk/sitesplus/992/news/46132|title=Take a look inside as Maes-y-Gwernen Hall opens its doors|publisher=Llwchwr Community Network|date=14 September 2017|accessdate=9 February 2019}}</ref> Williams's son, [[Jeremiah Williams (British politician)|Jeremiah Williams]], inherited the house in 1904 and invited [[David Lloyd George]] to stay there in 1918.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wales.nhs.uk/sitesplus/992/news/43612|title=Morriston celebrates centenary of David Lloyd George becoming PM|date=21 December 2016|publisher=Llwchwr Community Network|accessdate=9 February 2019}}</ref> An emergency medical hospital was built on the site in 1942.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://coflein.gov.uk/en/site/418613/details/morriston-hospital-swansea|title=Morriston Hospital|publisher=Coflein|accessdate=9 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nBy the late 1970s the hospital needed modernising. The design, which was undertaken by William Simpson using a nucleus layout which was capable of expansion,<ref>[http://www.nuffieldtrust.org.uk/ecomm/files/50_years_of_ideas.pdf 50 Years of Ideas in health care buildings] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110511203413/http://www.nuffieldtrust.org.uk/ecomm/files/50_years_of_ideas.pdf |date=May 11, 2011 }}</ref> was announced in December 1976 and planning permission granted in March 1978.<ref>[http://www2.swansea.gov.uk/Northgate/PlanningExplorer/Generic/StdDetails.aspx?PT=Constraints&TYPE=PL/PlanningPK.xml&PARAM0=468472&XSLT=/Northgate/PlanningExplorer/SiteFiles/Skins/Swansea_noborder/xslt/PL/PLDetails.xslt&FT=Planning%20Details&DAURI=PLANNING&XMLSIDE=/Northgate/PlanningExplorer/SiteFiles/Skins/swansea_noborder/Menus/PL.xml Online Standard Details] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120220015623/http://www2.swansea.gov.uk/Northgate/PlanningExplorer/Generic/StdDetails.aspx?PT=Constraints&TYPE=PL%2FPlanningPK.xml&PARAM0=468472&XSLT=%2FNorthgate%2FPlanningExplorer%2FSiteFiles%2FSkins%2FSwansea_noborder%2Fxslt%2FPL%2FPLDetails.xslt&FT=Planning%20Details&DAURI=PLANNING&XMLSIDE=%2FNorthgate%2FPlanningExplorer%2FSiteFiles%2FSkins%2Fswansea_noborder%2FMenus%2FPL.xml |date=2012-02-20 }}. .swansea.gov.uk (1978-03-30). Retrieved on 2013-08-12.</ref> Construction began in 1981 and the building opened in October 1985.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/written_answers/1985/dec/19/hospitals-1#column_285w |title=Hospitals |publisher=Hansard|date= 19 December 1985|accessdate=9 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe Welsh Centre for Burns and Plastic Surgery, which was designed to provide care for the whole population of 2.3 million across [[West Wales|West]], [[Mid Wales|Mid]] and [[South Wales]], moved to the site from [[St Lawrence Hospital, Chepstow]] in 1994.<ref name=burns>{{cite web|url=http://www.wales.nhs.uk/sitesplus/863/page/39301|title=The Welsh Centre for Burns and Plastic Surgery|publisher=Abertawe Bro Morgannwg University Health Board|accessdate=9 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015 the Health Board announced plans to expand the site with focus exclusively on the care of the sickest patients.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-38893085|title=\u00a3600m Arch bid to 'transform' west Wales NHS|publisher=BBC|accessdate=9 February 2019}}</ref> Further to those plans, a new [[cardiac]] unit, built at a cost of \u00a36.6 million, opened in August 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.walesonline.co.uk/news/health/new-66m-hospital-cardiac-unit-11725852|title=New \u00a36.6m hospital cardiac unit is unveiled in a bid to improve surgery waiting times|publisher=Wales online|date=9 August 2016|accessdate=9 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Services==\nThe hospital is the site of the major Emergency Department for Swansea and is considered by the Health Board to be the major trauma centre for [[South West Wales]]. In addition to general surgical and medical services, Morriston houses the Welsh Centre for Burns and Plastic Surgery.<ref name=burns/>\n\nThe hospital successfully trialled the use of robotic process automation to review rheumatology prescriptions in 2019. The Welsh government plans to set up an e-prescribing system.<ref>{{cite news |title=Automation pilot cuts prescription checking time by two-thirds |url=https://www.pharmaceutical-journal.com/20207500.article? |accessdate=24 February 2020 |publisher=Pharmaceutical Journal |date=20 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Public transport==\nThe hospital is served by a regular bus service between Morriston Hospital and [[Singleton Hospital]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bustimes.org/services/4-singleton-hospital-morriston-hospital|title=Singleton Hospital - Morriston Hospital|publisher=Bus times|accessdate=9 February 2019}}</ref>\n{{ftrmetro start}}\n{{rail line|previous=Heol Maes Egwlys|next=Terminus|route=Morriston Hospital|col=5B16F0 }}\n{{s-end}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{Official website}}\n* [https://111.wales.nhs.uk/LocalServices/ViewLocalService.aspx?id=3122&s=Hospital Morriston Hospital on the NHS Direct Wales website]\n* [https://hiw.org.uk/morriston-hospital Healthcare Inspectorate Wales inspection reports]\n\n{{Swansea Bay University Health Board}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Hospital buildings completed in 1941]]\n[[Category:Hospital buildings completed in 1985]]\n[[Category:NHS hospitals in Wales]]\n[[Category:1942 establishments in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Categor